V)` since `T₀` is in between but not part of either interval. \n\nAnother approach is to note that `zeroes_sum (Set.Ioo 0 V)` is the same as `zeroes_sum (Set.Ioo 0 T₀)` plus `zeroes_sum (Set.Ico T₀ V)`, because `(0, V)` is the disjoint union of `(0, T₀)` and `[T₀, V)` and the set of zeros with imaginary part exactly `T₀` is empty.\n\nThus:\n`sum (0, V) = sum (0, T₀) + sum [T₀, V)`.\n\nNow, `sum [T₀, V)` is exactly what `lemma_2_1` can bound by `B₁(T₀, V)` if `T₀ ≥ 1`.\n\nTherefore, we can proceed as follows:\n1. Show that `sum (0, V) = sum (0, T₀) + sum [T₀, V)` (since zeros cannot have `Im(ρ) = T₀`).\n2. Use `hS₀T₀` to bound `sum (0, T₀)` by `S₀`.\n3. Use `lemma_2_1` to bound `sum [T₀, V)` by `B₁(T₀, V)` (noting that `T₀ ≥ 1`).\n4. Combine the two inequalities to get `sum (0, V) < S₀ + B₁(T₀, V)`.\n\nBut for (1), we need to ensure no zeros have `Im(ρ) = T₀`. In Lean, this is probably true because the zeros are not real numbers (they come in pairs symmetric around the real axis).\n\nAlternatively, perhaps Lean's `zeroes_sum` already ignores the endpoints? \n\nLooking at the `zeroes_sum` definition (not shown in the Lean code), it is likely the sum over all zeros `ρ` with `Im ρ` in the specified set. Since the imaginary parts of zeros are not integers (they are usually transcendental), it's very unlikely that `Im(ρ) = T₀` unless `T₀` is constructed to be equal to one of them. Since `T₀` is taken to be `30610046000`, which is not expected to match any zero's imaginary part, we can safely ignore the possibility that some `ρ` has `Im(ρ) = T₀`.\n\nBut Lean may not allow such a handwavy argument, so perhaps we should instead use an interval like `[T₀, V)` and `(T₀, V)` and compare them, but perhaps it's easier to use `Set.Ico T₀ V` in Lean (which is `[T₀, V)`).\n\n#### Formal Approach\n\nHowever, there is actually a simpler approach in Lean: if we can show that for any `a < b`, the sum over `(0, b)` is less than or equal to the sum over `(0, a)` plus the sum over `[a, b)`