  - Then bound `sum (T₀, V)` by `sum [T₀, V)` (assuming no zeros at `T₀`), and then use `lemma_2_1` to bound `sum [T₀, V)` by `B₁(T₀, V)`.\n\nBut perhaps Lean can't directly prove that `sum (T₀, V) = sum [T₀, V)` if no zeros have `Im ρ = T₀`, unless we have such a lemma (which we don't).\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we could do:\n\nFor any `ε > 0`, `sum (T₀, V) = sum [T₀ + ε, V)` (again, assuming no zeros in `(T₀, T₀ + ε)`), but this seems too complicated.\n\n#### Concrete Approach:\n\nGiven that in Lean, the sum over `(T₀, V)` is `zeroes_sum Set.univ (Set.Ioo T₀ V) f`, and we want to relate it to `zeroes_sum Set.univ (Set.Ico T₀ V) f`, we can use that:\n`(T₀, V)` ⊆ `[T₀, V)` and the difference is at most the term at `T₀`, which is zero if no zeros have `Im ρ = T₀`.\n\nBut perhaps we can get away with this:\n\n```\nsum (0, V) ≤ sum (0, T₀) + sum [T₀, V)\n```\n\nif we can show that `sum (T₀, V) ≤ sum [T₀, V)` (as `sum [T₀, V) - sum (T₀, V)` is the term at `T₀` if it exists, and is 0 otherwise).\n\nBut the assumption here is that",
